-- ── Downtify ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Downtify is a free, open-source, self-hosted app that lets you download Spotify playlists, albums, and tracks as tagged audio files by matching them to YouTube Music, run entirely in a single Docker container.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2025, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$Portuguese$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Downtify Review 2026: Features & Setup Guide$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Downtify is a free, self-hosted, open-source Spotify downloader. Read about its features, Docker setup, supported formats, and how it compares to alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Downtify is a free, open-source, self-hosted application that downloads music referenced by Spotify links — individual tracks, albums, or entire playlists — and saves them locally as properly tagged audio files with embedded album art. It is created and maintained by a Brazilian developer who goes by henriquesebastiao, and the project is hosted on GitHub under the GPL-3.0 license. The public repository was created in February 2025, and the project has continued to see regular monthly releases through 2026, with hundreds of GitHub stars reflecting adoption in the self-hosting and home-lab community.

Technically, Downtify does not use the official Spotify API or require a Spotify Premium account or any API credentials. Instead, it reads the metadata that Spotify already exposes publicly on its embed pages for a given playlist, album, or track — artist names, track titles, album art, and ordering. Downtify then searches YouTube Music for the closest matching audio for each track, hands the resulting video off to yt-dlp to extract audio, uses ffmpeg to transcode it into the user's chosen format, and finally applies proper ID3 or equivalent metadata tags using the Python library mutagen. The application is built with a Python backend and a Vue.js frontend, communicates download progress to the browser in real time over WebSockets, and ships as a single Docker image, making it straightforward to deploy on a home server or NAS alongside other self-hosted media tools.

Download output supports five audio formats — MP3, FLAC, M4A, OGG, and OPUS — at a bitrate the user selects, and the tool can optionally organize downloaded files into folders by artist. A standout feature is the Playlist Monitor, which periodically checks a saved Spotify playlist and automatically downloads any newly added tracks without requiring the user to re-trigger anything, effectively turning a Spotify playlist into a self-updating local music library. Downtify also embeds lyrics — both plain text and time-synced (karaoke-style) lyrics sourced from the lrclib service — directly into the downloaded files. Beyond downloading, Downtify includes a built-in web-based music player with shuffle, repeat, and volume controls so users can listen to their downloaded library without a separate media app, and it can generate standard EXTM3U playlist files compatible with self-hosted media servers such as Jellyfin, Navidrome, and Plex. The interface is available in English, Spanish, and Brazilian Portuguese.

Because Downtify has no company, funding, or commercial pricing behind it, there is no pricing model to speak of beyond 'free and self-hosted' — users run their own instance and bear their own infrastructure costs (typically negligible, since it runs comfortably on a small home server). It is distributed exclusively as source code and as a prebuilt Docker image on GitHub Container Registry, with community packaging available for popular home-server app stores such as Umbrel, CasaOS, and HomeDock, which lets less technical users install it with a few clicks rather than a manual Docker command.

Downtify's target users are self-hosting enthusiasts, home-lab operators, and privacy-conscious listeners who want a personal, offline copy of music they already have access to via Spotify playlists, without depending on a third-party cloud service or requiring a Spotify Premium subscription. It sits in the same broad category as other community-built Spotify-to-local-file tools, such as spotDL and various forks including a project called downtify-premium built by another developer on top of the same idea, but Downtify differentiates itself with its polished built-in web player, its Playlist Monitor auto-sync feature, and its single-container Docker deployment model that fits cleanly into a self-hosted media stack. As with any tool that downloads copyrighted audio from streaming platforms, users are responsible for ensuring their use complies with Spotify's terms of service and applicable copyright law in their jurisdiction; the project itself is offered purely as open-source software with no warranty or affiliation with Spotify.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '0608cdcb-8ede-4cee-a620-9cc6d15af341';

