-- ── Drawpile ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Drawpile is a free, open-source collaborative drawing program that lets multiple people paint, sketch, and animate together in real time on the same canvas, with support for Windows, macOS, Linux, Android, and the web.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2014, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Small, largely volunteer-driven project maintained under a German non-profit organization$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Germany (Drawpile gemeinnützige UG, a non-profit organization)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$Multiple community-translated languages$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Drawpile Review 2026: Features, Platforms & Guide$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Drawpile is a free, open-source app for real-time collaborative drawing and animation. See 2026 features, supported platforms, pros, cons, and FAQs.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Drawpile is a free and open-source collaborative drawing program that allows multiple people to paint, sketch, and animate together in real time on a single shared canvas, with each participant's cursor and brushstrokes visible to everyone in the session as they happen. The software traces its lineage back to earlier work by developer Calle Laakkonen, with the project as branded today dating from 2014, as reflected in the copyright notice on its official site ('© 2014-2026 Drawpile Contributors'). Development is primarily carried out by a small core team, historically centered on a single lead developer, with a broader community contributing code, translations, and user support. The project is legally organized under Drawpile gemeinnützige UG, a German non-profit corporate structure explicitly set up 'for the public good,' a governance choice designed to keep the code owned by the public and prevent the project from being taken proprietary.

Technically, Drawpile is released under the GNU General Public License version 3 (GPLv3) for its software, while the project's website content is separately licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike 4.0. It is available natively on Windows, macOS, Linux, and Android, and a browser-based version extends access to platforms like iPad and iPhone without requiring installation. At its core, Drawpile functions as a networked painting application: a host starts or joins a drawing session on a server (either a self-hosted server or one of Drawpile's free official community servers), and every stroke made by any participant is transmitted and rendered live for everyone else in that session. Sessions can be left open to anyone or protected with a password to keep them private to invited collaborators, and a built-in chat function lets participants communicate while drawing.

On the creative-tooling side, Drawpile ships with more than 200 built-in brushes spanning multiple brush engines, along with a brush editor for building fully custom brushes, plus stroke stabilization to smooth shaky linework. It supports layers, layer groups, and blending modes for standard digital-painting workflows, along with shape tools, selections, transforms, and flood fill. Files can be exported to and imported from the OpenRaster (ORA) format as well as Photoshop's PSD format, easing interoperability with other digital art software. For animators, Drawpile includes a timeline with onion-skinning for frame-by-frame animation. More recent releases have added clipping layers, selection-masked brush strokes, OKLAB and spectral color painting modes, a redesigned selection action bar, and faster session reconnects. A distinctive resilience feature lets a user recover an interrupted session almost exactly where it left off if Drawpile crashes, if the operating system forces a reboot for updates, or if Android terminates the app in the background — replacing a traditional autosave mechanism. Drawpile also has a built-in timelapse recorder, accessible via the File menu's 'Make Timelapse' option, which can render a video of the entire drawing or animation process, optionally cropped to a specific region of the canvas.

Because Drawpile is free, open-source software with no company behind it, there is no pricing model, subscription, or paid tier: anyone can download the desktop or Android app at no cost, use the web version in a browser, and either self-host a session server or connect to one of the free official community servers that the project operates. This makes Drawpile distinct from most collaborative creative tools, which are typically commercial SaaS products with per-seat subscriptions.

Drawpile's target users are digital artists, art communities, classrooms, and hobbyists who want to draw together in real time — for collaborative illustration projects, live art battles or streams, teaching digital painting, or simply socializing while drawing with friends online. In the collaborative whiteboard and drawing space, it is often compared to tools such as Krita's (limited) collaborative features, Magma, or general-purpose whiteboard tools like Miro used informally for drawing, though those alternatives are either commercial or not purpose-built for real-time multi-user painting the way Drawpile is. Drawpile's core differentiation is that it is a dedicated, full-featured painting application with genuine real-time multi-user synchronization built in from the ground up, released as free software with governance structured specifically to keep it that way, rather than a commercial whiteboard tool with basic drawing functionality bolted on.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '24cc901e-5be4-49f1-a1da-9b6b8e0ccdd4';

