-- ── DrChrono ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$DrChrono is a cloud-based, mobile-first EHR, practice management, and medical billing platform for medical practices, originally built as one of the first iPad-native electronic health record systems.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription (tiered, per provider)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Custom quote (reported range roughly $199-$600+/provider/month depending on tier)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2009, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Part of EverCommerce (public company); mid-size team under the EverHealth solutions group$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Sunnyvale/Mountain View, California, USA (now part of EverCommerce, headquartered in Denver, Colorado)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$DrChrono Review 2026: EHR Pricing & Features$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$DrChrono is a cloud-based, mobile-first EHR and practice management platform. See 2026 pricing tiers, features, pros, cons, and alternatives for medical practices.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$DrChrono is a cloud-based electronic health record (EHR), practice management, and medical billing platform built for medical practices, best known for having launched in 2009 as one of the first EHR systems built natively for the iPad, at a time when most competitors were still tethered to desktop browsers or on-premise servers. The company was founded by Michael Nusimow and Daniel Kivatinos in California, with early operations based in the Mountain View and Sunnyvale area of Silicon Valley. DrChrono's mobile-first bet distinguished it early on: by building for tablets from day one rather than retrofitting a desktop product, it positioned itself to serve physicians who wanted to review charts and enter notes at the point of care rather than returning to a desktop workstation.

On November 2, 2021, EverCommerce Inc., a publicly traded vertical software company, announced a definitive agreement to acquire DrChrono, with the deal closing on November 18, 2021 for a reported price of roughly 180 million dollars, though EverCommerce did not disclose official financial terms at the time. Following the acquisition, DrChrono became part of EverCommerce's EverHealth solutions group, which bundles several healthcare-focused software products under one corporate umbrella. DrChrono has continued to operate under its own brand and product name since the acquisition, and the platform itself has kept expanding, most recently adding AI-driven tools such as automated medical speech-to-text and an AI clinical scribe product branded EverHealth Scribe.

Functionally, DrChrono combines several traditionally separate systems into one suite: an EHR for clinical documentation and charting, practice management tools for appointment scheduling and calendar management, revenue cycle management and medical billing (including claims submission), a patient portal for online scheduling and communication, and e-prescribing. It also offers a well-documented medical API that lets third-party developers and health-tech companies build integrations on top of DrChrono's platform, a differentiator that has made it popular among digital health startups that need EHR connectivity. The platform supports lab integrations, e-faxing, and both text and phone appointment reminders, with the specific volume of included texts, calls, and faxes varying by pricing tier.

DrChrono is sold in three tiers — Foundation, Growth, and Premium — priced per provider per month, though exact published pricing is not listed on its marketing site and prospective customers are directed to request a custom quote. Third-party pricing trackers report DrChrono's cost typically starting in the range of 199 to 250 dollars per provider per month for the Foundation tier, rising to roughly 300 to 600-plus dollars per provider per month for Growth and Premium plans that add more automated revenue cycle management workflows and AI-driven performance tools. Feature allotments scale with tier: for example, Foundation includes 250 text and 100 phone reminders per month along with 500 e-faxes, Growth doubles most of those allotments, and Premium goes further still with 1,000 texts, 750 calls, and 2,000 e-faxes, while all tiers include unlimited email reminders and staff accounts. Add-ons such as extended lab integration services (around 30 dollars per provider per month) and clinical speech-to-text or the EverHealth Scribe AI tool are available across tiers, though the AI scribe and speech-to-text tools are bundled into the Premium tier by default rather than sold separately.

DrChrono's core customers are solo practitioners, small and mid-size medical practices, and specialty clinics that want an all-in-one, cloud-based system rather than stitching together separate scheduling, billing, and charting software. Its most direct competitors include Kareo (also part of Tebra), athenahealth, eClinicalWorks, and, for larger health systems, Epic — though Epic and athenahealth generally target much larger enterprise and hospital-system deployments than DrChrono's typical small-practice customer base. DrChrono differentiates itself through its mobile- and tablet-first design heritage, its open, developer-friendly API, and, since joining EverCommerce, integration with EverHealth's broader suite of healthcare business tools, positioning it as a flexible, API-extensible EHR option for independent practices that value mobility and third-party integrations over the deep enterprise workflow customization that larger hospital-focused platforms offer.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '658c8cb8-ea59-4b89-bc57-b008fda4a4bd';

